text.tspan: In Fig 1. of the Attractor Scaffolding paper, it's quite easy to fall into
the trap of thinking that a given output row is what you get when the
network state is as shown in the corresponding input row. With the
network working shown in that paper (box, right), you actually have
to consult 5 rows of the table. It's possible to arrange the wiring so that
you DO have that nice relationship between input row and output row.
So, should we have used it?
Consider n=5, k=5. Kaufman says there is one possible wiring
diagram of the 'Grand Ensemble'. If the wiring is set up as in A, a neat
table can be drawn. In this table, the input i for any gene a-e,
always originates from gene a (red), input ii is always
from b (blue), iii from c (green) etc. However, the inputs
can still be swapped around. Compare this connectivity with
the connectivity defined in the Attractor Scaffolding paper. The only
difference is the definition of the inputs to which each connection is wired.
Now consider n=5, k=4. How to remove the one input? You have
to choose. There are many possibilities. The most obvious
k=n-1 is for self to not influence its own future state. And here,
we see that the relationship between input index and the
originating gene state (i.e. the colour) is lost. Because of this, we
don't use the arrangement in A for k=n networks.
Note: Another possible n=5, k=4 wiring is to keep the
ii=input yellow etc. The resulting system has an input-only relationship
for gene e; the value of gene e is not able to influence the rest of the
network. This is 'canalyzing for gene e' because the value of e cannot
affect the rest of the network's outcome.
Should I have used an alternative wiring from that used in the Attractor Scaffolding Paper?
